FOUNDRY IAM

SAML 2.0 PROTOCOL EXTENSION

Feature Specification — Phase 2





Document Type

Feature Extension Spec

Phase

Phase 2 — Post-MVP

Estimated Build

5–7 engineering days

Dependencies

MVP platform live + paying tenants

Trigger

First enterprise customer requesting SAML

Revenue Impact

Unlocks enterprise deals ($1k–$5k/month ACV)



This document specifies the SAML 2.0 extension to the Foundry IAM platform. It covers the protocol background, what Keycloak provides out-of-the-box, the control plane changes required, the UI additions to the portal, the API contract additions, the test matrix, and the implementation sequence. An engineer receiving only this document should be able to implement the feature without access to the core platform specification.



SECTION 1

What SAML 2.0 Is and Why Enterprise Customers Demand It





1.1 Protocol Overview

SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language) is a 2005 OASIS standard for exchanging authentication and authorisation data between an Identity Provider (IdP) and a Service Provider (SP). Unlike OIDC which uses JSON and REST, SAML uses XML documents transmitted via HTTP redirects or form POSTs.



In the Foundry IAM context:

Foundry IAM (Keycloak) acts as the Identity Provider (IdP)

The customer's application (or a third-party SaaS) acts as the Service Provider (SP)

The customer's end users authenticate at Foundry IAM and receive a SAML Assertion

The SP trusts the signed assertion without re-authenticating the user



1.2 Why Enterprise Customers Need It

Scenario

Why SAML Is Required

Legacy enterprise SaaS

Salesforce, SAP, ServiceNow, Workday — all use SAML for SSO. These platforms have no OIDC support in many enterprise deployments.

Corporate IT policy

Many enterprise IT departments mandate SAML for all third-party integrations. OIDC is not yet universally accepted in traditional IT governance frameworks.

Existing Okta / Azure AD setup

Large organisations already have Okta or Azure AD as their IdP. They want Foundry IAM to act as a SAML SP to those upstream IdPs, or as a SAML IdP for downstream apps.

Compliance requirements

SAML is explicitly named in SOC 2, ISO 27001, and FedRAMP SSO requirements in many organisations.

Deal blocker

Without SAML, enterprise procurement teams will reject the platform regardless of other capabilities.



1.3 SAML vs OIDC — Key Differences Engineers Must Understand

Dimension

OIDC (MVP — already built)

SAML 2.0 (this spec)

Data format

JSON (JWT)

XML (SAML Assertion)

Transport

REST/HTTP redirect + JSON

HTTP redirect or HTTP POST (form)

Assertion

JWT signed with RS256

XML signed with XML-DSig (RSA-SHA256)

Token size

Small (< 2KB typical)

Large (5KB–20KB typical, XML verbose)

Discovery

Well-known JSON document

XML Metadata document

SSO initiation

Can be SP-initiated or IdP-initiated

Both SP-initiated and IdP-initiated (important for enterprise)

Logout

OIDC front-channel/back-channel

SAML Single Logout (SLO) — more complex

Keycloak support

Native, zero config

Native, requires SP registration per client





SECTION 2

What Keycloak Provides (The Free 70%)





Keycloak includes a production-grade SAML 2.0 IdP implementation. This is the primary reason the SAML extension is 5–7 days rather than months. The engineering work is in the control plane wiring, the portal UX, and the SP metadata management — not in implementing SAML itself.



2.1 Keycloak SAML Capabilities (Included, No Code)

SAML 2.0 Identity Provider for any realm

SP-initiated SSO (application sends AuthnRequest to Keycloak)

IdP-initiated SSO (Keycloak pushes assertion to SP without AuthnRequest)

HTTP Redirect binding and HTTP POST binding

SAML Assertion signing (RSA-SHA256, RSA-SHA512)

Assertion encryption (AES-128-CBC, AES-256-CBC)

Attribute mapping (map Keycloak user attributes to SAML attributes)

SAML Single Logout (SLO) — both SP and IdP initiated

SP registration via XML Metadata import

IdP Metadata export per realm (XML document)

NameID formats: persistent, transient, email, unspecified



2.2 What Keycloak Does NOT Do Automatically

Engineering Work Required

These gaps are where the 5–7 days of work goes. Keycloak handles the protocol; we must build the management layer on top.



No API for our control plane to programmatically register SAML Service Providers — we must call the Keycloak Admin REST API

No portal UI for customers to register their SP metadata or download IdP metadata

No storage of SP metadata in our control plane database (for auditing, billing, listing)

No per-client attribute mapping UI in our portal

No validation of uploaded SP metadata documents before registration

No automated signing certificate rotation notifications





SECTION 3

Architecture & Data Model Changes





3.1 How SAML Fits Into the Existing Architecture

No new services are required. SAML is an additional protocol layer on top of existing Keycloak realms. The control plane API gains new endpoints. The portal gains new pages. Keycloak gains SAML client registrations per realm.



Existing flow (OIDC):

  Customer App → Keycloak realm (OIDC) → JWT → Customer API



New flow (SAML IdP mode — most common enterprise use case):

  Enterprise SaaS (SP) → Keycloak realm (SAML IdP) → SAML Assertion → Enterprise SaaS



New flow (SAML SP mode — customer's Keycloak acting as SP to upstream IdP):

  End User → Keycloak realm (SAML SP) → Corporate Azure AD / Okta (IdP) → SAML Assertion → Keycloak → OIDC JWT → Customer App

  [Note: SAML SP mode is handled by the Custom Federation spec, not this document]



